<h3>System details — what's inside, and in what order to read</h3>

<h4>Introduction — first steps with Claude Code (6 docs)</h4>
<p>The entry System: what Claude Code is and how to get started. <a href="#!welcome">Welcome</a> explains the tool, <a href="#!install">Install &amp; Start</a> covers installation and auth, and <a href="#!commands">Everyday Use</a> teaches slash commands, CLAUDE.md, and plan mode. Three extension axes follow — <a href="#!skills">Skills</a>, <a href="#!mcp">MCP Servers</a>, and <a href="#!hooks">Hooks</a>. Its concepts (install, slash commands, CLAUDE.md) carry straight into the Tutorial and OMC Systems.</p>

<h4>Tutorial (Basics) — the foundation course (12 docs)</h4>
<p>The documented basics course, gated by <a href="#!ccb-overview">Course overview</a>. Build fundamentals with <a href="#!ccb-what">What is Claude Code</a> → <a href="#!ccb-terminal">Terminal basics</a> → <a href="#!ccb-claudemd">CLAUDE.md</a>, then work through hands-on examples — <a href="#!ccb-research-web">research &amp; websites</a>, <a href="#!ccb-design-system">design-system extraction</a>, <a href="#!ccb-papers">Hugging Face papers</a> — before expanding into <a href="#!ccb-skills">building skills</a>, <a href="#!ccb-plugins">plugins</a>, and <a href="#!ccb-agents">building agents</a>, closing with <a href="#!ccb-manage">usage &amp; context management</a> and <a href="#!ccb-tips">useful features</a>.</p>

<h4>Skill — skills deep dive (12 docs)</h4>
<p>A first-principles System on why and how skills work. <a href="#!skl-overview">Overview</a> and <a href="#!skl-coding-agent">The birth of the coding agent</a> set the background; <a href="#!skl-what">What is a skill</a>, <a href="#!skl-strengths">Strengths</a>, <a href="#!skl-context">Context window &amp; tools</a>, and <a href="#!skl-progressive">Progressive loading</a> cover the core mechanics; <a href="#!skl-structure">SKILL.md structure</a>, <a href="#!skl-examples">Example skills</a>, <a href="#!skl-install">Install &amp; use</a>, <a href="#!skl-security">Security</a>, and <a href="#!skl-creating">Creating skills</a> cover practice. <a href="#!skl-wrap">Engineering layers &amp; Q&amp;A</a> relates skills to MCP and harnesses, bridging to the automation branch.</p>

<h4>Second Brain — 5 levels of knowledge management (9 docs)</h4>
<p>A staged model of personal and organizational knowledge management, from <strong>level 1 (find exactly) to level 5 (autonomous brain OS)</strong>. Start with <a href="#!sb-intro">What is a second brain</a>, get the full picture at the hub <a href="#!sb-levels">The 5 levels at a glance</a>, then read <a href="#!sb-level1">level 1</a> through <a href="#!sb-level5">level 5</a> in order. <a href="#!sb-context-connections">What goes in, what stays out</a> and <a href="#!sb-choose">Find your level · scale to teams</a> guide real-world adoption. The LLM Wiki System is a concrete implementation of level 2.</p>

<h4>LLM Wiki — an Obsidian-based knowledge vault (11 docs)</h4>
<p>The methodology System for running an LLM-friendly wiki on Obsidian vaults. After the <a href="#!llmw-overview">overview</a>, the hub <a href="#!llmw-vaults">Vault system</a> sets the structure; <a href="#!llmw-capture">knowledge capture</a>, <a href="#!llmw-metadata">note metadata</a>, <a href="#!llmw-links">links &amp; cross-vault references</a>, <a href="#!llmw-cards">wiki cards</a>, and <a href="#!llmw-system">system files &amp; rules</a> define the operating rules. <a href="#!llmw-onboard">Onboarding practice</a>, <a href="#!llmw-ingest-query-lint">Ingest·Query·Lint</a>, and <a href="#!llmw-clipper-query">Web clipper &amp; Query in practice</a> form the hands-on axis, closed by <a href="#!llmw-philosophy">Usage &amp; philosophy</a>.</p>

<h4>Harness Engineering — the agent-team methodology (12 docs)</h4>
<p>Home of the AI World's <strong>most-linked hub</strong> (<a href="#!hns-anatomy">Anatomy &amp; impact</a>, 11 links). Grasp the concept via <a href="#!hns-overview">Overview</a> → <a href="#!hns-what">What is harness engineering</a> → <a href="#!hns-anatomy">Anatomy &amp; impact</a>, then practice with <a href="#!hns-install">installing the meta-harness skill</a>, <a href="#!hns-run">running a harness</a>, and <a href="#!hns-review">reviewing the output</a>. <a href="#!hns-kitchen">The kitchen analogy</a>, <a href="#!hns-team">Agent teams &amp; context</a>, and <a href="#!hns-core">The three core elements</a> explain the mechanics; <a href="#!hns-usecases">use cases</a>, <a href="#!hns-hundred">Harness 100</a>, and <a href="#!hns-tools">tool extensions</a> cover applications.</p>

<h4>Harness Plugin — harnesses for real ERP work (10 docs)</h4>
<p>The plugin System that applies harness methodology to <strong>ERP customization work</strong>. After <a href="#!hnp-intro">Intro</a>, <a href="#!hnp-concepts">Key concepts</a>, and <a href="#!hnp-install">Install</a>, jump straight into practice with <a href="#!hnp-first-run">First run (sales orders)</a>. <a href="#!hnp-architecture">How it works — 6 stages</a>, <a href="#!hnp-agents-skills">Agent &amp; skill design</a>, and <a href="#!hnp-verify">Verification &amp; _workspace</a> explain the internals; <a href="#!hnp-scenarios">the scenario board</a>, <a href="#!hnp-hundred">Harness 100 &amp; performance</a>, and <a href="#!hnp-commands">commands</a> cover usage. Here the Harness Engineering theory meets the business domain.</p>

<h4>OMC Plugin — execution modes and autonomy (13 docs)</h4>
<p>The usage System for the oh-my-claudecode plugin — the largest one (13 docs). After <a href="#!omc-intro">Intro</a> and <a href="#!omc-concepts">Key terms</a>, set up with the hub <a href="#!omc-install">Install</a> and <a href="#!omc-doctor">Install diagnostics</a>, then learn the features: <a href="#!omc-modes">execution modes</a> (autopilot · ralph · ultrawork · team), <a href="#!omc-agents">agents &amp; skills</a>, <a href="#!omc-hooks">hooks &amp; memory</a>, and <a href="#!omc-tools">advanced tools</a>. <a href="#!omc-workflows">Real-world scenarios</a>, <a href="#!omc-windows">Windows notes</a>, <a href="#!omc-cost">cost &amp; performance</a>, <a href="#!omc-commands">command reference</a>, and <a href="#!omc-quickref">quick reference</a> round out operations.</p>

